\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard
Factor analysis is a very popular method in statistics that reduces linear
 dimensionality of a particular model.
 The best way to understand factor analysis is to consider a generative
 model.
 A basic factor analysis model is of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=Lf+\epsilon,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the observed random vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathbf{R}^{r}$
\end_inset

 is a random vector of common factor variables or scores, 
\begin_inset Formula $L\in\mathbf{R}^{n\times r}$
\end_inset

 is a matrix of factor loadings, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of uncorrelated random variables.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The observed random vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 may contain series of achievement tests, psychological evaluation, intellectual
 performance etc.
 Without loss of generality, we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is mean-centered 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}(x)=0$
\end_inset

, the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 are uncorrelated, and the covariance matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the identity matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{cov}(\epsilon)=D=\mathbf{diag}(d_{1},d_{2},\ldots,d_{n}).$
\end_inset

 Then the covariance matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 can be written as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Sigma=X+D,
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $X=LL^{T}$
\end_inset

 is the covariance matrix corresponding to the common factors.
\end_layout

\end_body
